04920nam a2200625Ia 9780801461910DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)987933247  a97808014619107 a10.7591/97808014619102doi  a(DE-B1597)481714  a(OCoLC)732956584  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ792.C89bZ34 2008eb 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a305.23094371/09042221 aZahra, Tara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKidnapped Souls :bNational Indifference and the Battle for Children in the Bohemian Lands, 1900–1948 /cTara Zahra. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b5 halftones, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Maps -- tPreface -- tList of Archives and Abbreviations -- tNote on Places and Names -- tIntroduction -- t1. “Czech Schools for Czech Children!” -- t2. Teachers, Orphans, and Social Workers -- t3. Warfare, Welfare, and the End of Empire -- t4. Reclaiming Children for the Nation -- t5. Freudian Nationalists and Heimat Activists -- t6. Borderland Children and Volkstumsarbeit under Nazi Rule -- t7. Stay-at-Home Nationalism -- t8. Reich-Loyal Czech Nationalism -- tEpilogue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout the nineteenth and into the early decades of the twentieth century, it was common for rural and working-class parents in the Czech-German borderlands to ensure that their children were bilingual by sending them to live with families who spoke the "other" language. As nationalism became a more potent force in Central Europe, however, such practices troubled pro-German and pro-Czech activists, who feared that the children born to their nation could literally be "lost" or "kidnapped" from the national community through such experiences and, more generally, by parents who were either flexible about national belonging or altogether indifferent to it.Highlighting this indifference to nationalism—and concerns about such apathy among nationalists—Kidnapped Souls offers a surprising new perspective on Central European politics and society in the first half of the twentieth century. Drawing on Austrian, Czech, and German archives, Tara Zahra shows how nationalists in the Bohemian Lands worked to forge political cultures in which children belonged more rightfully to the national collective than to their parents. Through their educational and social activism to fix the boundaries of nation and family, Zahra finds, Czech and German nationalists reveal the set of beliefs they shared about children, family, democracy, minority rights, and the relationship between the individual and the collective. Zahra shows that by 1939 a vigorous tradition of Czech-German nationalist competition over children had created cultures that would shape the policies of the Nazi occupation and the Czech response to it.The book's concluding chapter weighs the prehistory and consequences of the postwar expulsion of German families from the Bohemian Lands. Kidnapped Souls is a significant contribution to our understanding of the genealogy of modern nationalism in Central Europe and a groundbreaking exploration of the ways in which children have been the objects of political contestation when national communities have sought to shape, or to reshape, their futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146191040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801461910423Coveruhttps://ww